# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: geoffrey-c-ward
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] In 2019, he released his documentary *Citizen K*, about Russian President Vladimir Putin and the Russian billionaire exile Mikhail Khodorkovsky.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] Gibney was born in New York City, the son of Harriet (Harvey) and journalist Frank Gibney.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] His stepfather was William Sloane Coffin.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] After attending Pomfret School, Gibney earned his bachelor's degree from Yale University and later attended the UCLA Film School.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] Gibney developed an anti-authoritarian view from the journalism career of his father: "They say to succeed you're supposed to suck up and kick down.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] Well, he was the classic guy who sucked down and kicked up, which is never a good career path!
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] At *Life*, fired." His stepfather was equally an influence on him.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] "There was something about my father, my mother, and then my stepfather, I think they all ruddered against authority in their own peculiar ways.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] He served as executive producer of the documentary *No End in Sight* (2007).
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] His film *Gonzo: The Life and Work of Dr.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] Thompson* (2008) is a documentary based on Hunter S.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] Thompson's life and his "Gonzo" style of journalism.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] Several films he directed and/or produced have been screened at the Cannes, Sundance, Toronto and Tribeca Film Festivals.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] Gibney frequently employs a narrative strategy akin to that of Ken Burns in which the filmmaker relies on testimony from those involved in the events recounted together with voice-over narration.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] Gibney's *Taxi to the Dark Side* premiered at the 2007 Tribeca Film Festival where it won Best Documentary.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] The film probes the killing of a taxi driver named Dilawar at Bagram Air Force Base in Afghanistan.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] Gibney is president of Jigsaw Productions, which produces independent films, documentaries and television series.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] On June 16, 2020, Imagine Entertainment, a film, television and documentary production company run by Brian Grazer and Ron Howard, invested in and acquired an ownership stake in the company.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] Gibney has been honored by the Yale Film Studies program for his contributions to film culture.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] His 2013 film *We Steal Secrets: The Story of WikiLeaks*, is a comprehensive look at WikiLeaks, Julian Assange, and Chelsea Manning.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] The Wikileaks organization itself has objected to the way Gibney portrayed it, and has posted a line-by-line rebuttal to the entire film.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] In 2015, Gibney received the inaugural Hitchens Prize, awarded in honor of the late writer Christopher Hitchens.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] Gibney had previously collaborated with Hitchens on a documentary film adaption of Hitchens's book *The Trial of Henry Kissinger*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] In 2023, Gibney showed the first part of two-part documentary at the Berlin film festival called *Boom!
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] Boris Becker*, concerning the life of troubled German tennis star Boris Becker.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] In March 2023 he announced that he was “several months” into a documentary film called *Musk,* about entrepreneur Elon Musk.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] In December 2024, it was reported that Gibney and Anonymous Content were working on a documentary on Luigi Mangione, the alleged shooter involved in the killing of UnitedHealthCare CEO Brian Thompson.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] Gibney writes for *The Atlantic*, and has written for *Huffington Post* and other publications.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] On June 19, 2008, Gibney's company filed for arbitration, arguing that THINKFilm failed to properly distribute and promote his film *Taxi to the Dark Side*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] He sued for over a million dollars in damages and stated that the film has grossed only $280,000.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alex-gibney] Gibney has been a resident of Summit, New Jersey, and, as of 2025, lives in New Harbor, Maine.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] The Knopf publishing house is associated with the borzoi logo in its colophon, which was designed by co-founder Blanche Knopf in 1925.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Knopf Sr. along with Blanche Knopf, on a $5,000 advance from his father, Samuel Knopf.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] The first office was located in New York's Candler Building.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] The publishing house was officially incorporated in 1918, with Alfred Knopf as president, Blanche Knopf as vice president, and Samuel Knopf as treasurer.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] From the start, Knopf focused on European translations and high-brow works of literature.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Among their initial publications were French author Émile Augier's *Four Plays*, Russian writer Nikolai Gogol's *Taras Bulba*, Polish novelist Stanisław Przybyszewski's novel *Homo Sapiens*, and French writer Guy de Maupassant's *Yvette, a Novelette, and Ten Other Stories*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] During World War I these books were cheap to obtain and helped establish Knopf as an American firm publishing European works.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Their first bestseller was a new edition of *Green Mansions*, a novel by W.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Hudson which went through nine printings by 1919 and sold over 20,000 copies.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Their first original American novel, *The Three Black Pennys* by Joseph Hergesheimer, was published in 1917.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] With the start of the 1920s Knopf began using innovative advertising techniques to draw attention to their books and authors.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Beginning in 1920, Knopf produced a chapbook for the purpose of promoting new books.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] *The Borzoi* was published periodically over the years, the first being a hardback called *The Borzoi* and sometimes quarterly as *The Borzoi Quarterly*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] For Floyd Dell's coming-of-age novel, *Moon-Calf*, they paid men to walk the streets of the financial and theatre districts dressed in artist costumes with sandwich boards.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] The placards had a copy of the book for browsing and directed interested buyers to local book shops.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] The unique look of their books along with their expertise in advertising their authors drew Willa Cather to leave her previous publisher Houghton Mifflin to join Alfred A.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] As she was still under contract for her novels, the Knopfs suggested publishing a collection of her short stories, *Youth and the Bright Medusa*, in 1920.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Cather was pleased with the results and the advertisement of the book in *The New Republic* and would go on to publish sixteen books with Knopf, including their first Pulitzer Prize winner, *One of Ours*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Before they had married, Alfred had promised Blanche that they would be equal partners in the publishing company, but it was clear by the company's fifth anniversary that this was not to be the case.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Knopf published a celebratory fifth-anniversary book in which Alfred was the focus of anecdotes by authors and Blanche's name was only mentioned once to note that "Mrs.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] This despite ample evidence from authors and others that Blanche was in fact the soul of the company.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] This was covered extensively in *The Lady with the Borzoi* by Laura Claridge.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] In 1923, Knopf also started publishing periodicals, beginning with *The American Mercury*, founded by H.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Mencken and George Jean Nathan, which it published through 1934.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Also in 1923, Knopf published Kahlil Gibran's *The Prophet*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Knopf had published Gibran's earlier works which had disappointing sales.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] In its first year, *The Prophet* only sold 1,159 copies.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] It would double sales the next year and keep doubling becoming one of the firm's most successful books.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Approaching its 100 year anniversary in 2023, *The Prophet* has been translated into over 100 languages and has never gone out of print for Knopf.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] In the 1920s, Knopf sometimes withdrew or censored their books when threatened by John Sumner, such as Floyd Dell's *Janet March* or George Egerton's 1899 translation of *Hunger*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Koshland joined the company in 1934, and worked with the firm for more than fifty years, rising to take the positions of president and chairman of the board.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Blanche became president in 1957 when Alfred became chairman of the board, and worked steadily for the firm until her death in 1966.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Alfred Knopf retired in 1972, becoming chairman emeritus of the firm until his death in 1984.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Alfred Knopf also had a summer home in Purchase, New York.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Following the Good Neighbor policy, Blanche Knopf visited South America in 1942, so the firm could start producing texts from there.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] She was one of the first publishers to visit Europe after World War II.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Her trips, and those of other editors, brought in new writers from Europe, South America, and Asia.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Alfred traveled to Brazil in 1961, which spurred a corresponding interest on his part in South America.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Penn Publishing Company was acquired in 1943.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] The Knopfs' son, Alfred "Pat" Jr., was hired on as secretary and trade books manager after the war.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] In 1957, editor Judith Jones joined Knopf.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Jones, who had discovered *Anne Frank: Diary of a Young Girl* while working at Doubleday, acquired Simone Beck, Louisette Bertholle and Julia Child's *Mastering the Art of French Cooking* for Knopf.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Jones would remain with Knopf, retiring in 2011 as a senior editor and vice-president after a career that included working with John Updike and Anne Tyler.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Pat Knopf left his parents' publishing company in 1959 to launch his own, Atheneum Publishers, with two other partners.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] The story made the front page of *The New York Times*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] In a 1957 advertisement in *The Atlantic Monthly*, Alfred A.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] The credo includes a list of what Knopf's beliefs for publishing including the statement that he never published an unworthy book.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] In 1960, Random House acquired Alfred A.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] It is believed that the decision to sell was prompted by Alfred A.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Knopf Jr., leaving Knopf to found his own book company, Atheneum Books, in 1959.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Since its founding, Knopf has paid close attention to design and typography, employing notable designers and typographers including William Addison Dwiggins, Harry Ford, Steven Heller, Chip Kidd, Lorraine Louie, Peter Mendelsund, Bruce Rogers, Rudolf Ruzicka, and Beatrice Warde.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Knopf books conclude with an unnumbered page titled "A Note on the Type", which describes the history of the typeface used for the book.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] In addition, Knopf books date the year of the book's current printing on the title page.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Knopf published textbooks until 1988, when Random House's schools and colleges division was sold to McGraw Hill.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] In 1991, Knopf revived the "Everyman's Library" series, originally published in England in the early 20th century.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] This series consists of classics of world literature in affordable hardcover editions.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] The series has grown over the years to include lines of *Children's Classics* and *Pocket Poets*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Random House was acquired by Bertelsmann AG in 1998.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] In late 2008 and early 2009, the Knopf Publishing Group merged with Doubleday to form the Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Random House has been owned since its 2013 merger of Penguin Group by Penguin Random House, a joint venture between Bertelsmann (53%) and Pearson PLC (47%).
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Many of Knopf's hardcover books are published later as Vintage paperbacks.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Vintage Books is a sister imprint of Random House.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] In October 2012, Bertelsmann entered into talks with rival conglomerate Pearson plc, over the possibility of combining their respective publishing companies, Random House and Penguin Group.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] The merger was completed on 1 July 2013 and the new company is Penguin Random House.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Bertelsmann owned 53% of the joint venture while Pearson owned 47%.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] At the time of the acquisition the combined companies controlled 25% of the book business, with more than 10,000 employees and 250 independent publishing imprints and with about $3.9 billion in annual revenues.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] The move to consolidate was to provide leverage against Amazon.com and battle the shrinking state of bookstores.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] In 2015, Knopf celebrated its 100th anniversary by publishing a commemorative book, *Alfred A.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] While there have been many notable editors at Knopf there have only been four editors-in-chief: Alfred A.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Knopf, Sr., Robert Gottlieb, Sonny Mehta (who died in 2019) and Jordan Pavlin.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Knopf also employed literary scouts to good advantage.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Hamilton, Kazuo Ishiguro, John Keegan, Nella Larsen, John le Carré, Jack London, Gabriel García Márquez, Cormac McCarthy, Toni Morrison, Alice Munro, Haruki Murakami, Cynthia Ozick, Christopher Paolini, Edgar Allan Poe, Ezra Pound, Anne Rice, Dorothy Richardson, Stephen M.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Silverman, Oswald Spengler, Susan Swan, Donna Tartt, Barbara W.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Tuchman, Anne Tyler, John Updike, Andrew Vachss, James D.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] The logo for Knopf is a Russian wolfhound or Borzoi.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/alfred-a-knopf] Blanche Knopf suggested the Borzoi for the logo to imply motion and the logo was used on both the spine and the title page of their books.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-experience] *American Experience* is produced primarily by WGBH-TV in Boston, Massachusetts, though occasionally in the early seasons it was co-produced by other PBS stations such as WNET (Channel 13) in New York City.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-experience] Some of the *American Experience* programs were produced prior to the formal creation of the series.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-experience] *Vietnam: A Television History* was one of them, airing originally in 1983 after six years in development.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-experience] Also, in 2006, *American Experience* rebroadcast *Eyes on the Prize: America's Civil Rights Years*, the first half of the 1986 documentary series about the Civil Rights Movement of the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-experience] In July 2025, WGBH announced that *American Experience* would end new production and switch exclusively to rereleasing past episodes after airing an abbreviated 37th season that fall and that the series' staff was being laid off.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-experience] WGBH CEO Susan Goldberg attributed the decision to "severe cuts in federal funding for public media." Work had been halted in May on six films, and no new documentaries will be produced until further notice since this is the "most expensive show funded by PBS" on a per hour basis.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-experience] A DVD boxset collecting episodes about United States presidents was released on August 26, 2008.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-experience] A DVD boxset for the five-part documentary *We Shall Remain* was released on May 12, 2009.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-experience] The collection was updated to include the documentary on Bill Clinton's presidency on August 28, 2012, and the documentary on George W.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] From 1947 to 1949 the American Association for State and Local History published a house organ, ***American Heritage: A Journal of Community History***.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] In September 1949, AASLH launched the magazine with broader scope for the general public, but keeping certain features geared to educators and historical societies.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] In 1954, AASLH sold the magazine to a quartet of writers and editors from Time, Inc. including James Parton, Oliver Jensen, Joseph J.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] Thorndike and founding editor Bruce Catton, the Pulitzer Prize-winning historian of the Civil War.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] They formed the **American Heritage Publishing Company** and introduced the hardcover, 120-page advertising-free "magazine" with Volume 6, Number 1 in December 1954.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] Though, in essence, an entirely new magazine, the publishers kept the volume numbering because the previous incarnation had been indexed in the *Readers' Guide to Periodical Literature*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] Each year begins in December and continues through the following October, published every other month.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] For example, Volume XXV issues are December 1973, February 1974, April 1974, June 1974, August 1974, and October 1974.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] Bruce Catton remained with the magazine for 25 years until his death in 1979 and published over 100 essays.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] In 1964, David McCullough began his writing career as an editor and writer for *American Heritage*, which he sometimes calls "my graduate school".
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] McCullough wrote numerous articles for the magazine.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] He turned his article for the June 1966 issue on the Johnstown Flood, *Run for Your Lives*, into a full-length book titled, *The Johnstown Flood*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] When it became an unexpected bestseller, McCullough left the magazine in 1968 to commit full-time to writing.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] Later *American Heritage* articles by McCullough on the transcontinental railroad and Harry Truman also became bestselling books.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] McGraw-Hill purchased the American Heritage Publishing Company in 1969.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] By 1980, costs made the hardcover version prohibitive for a regular subscription.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] Subscribers could choose the new regular newsstand high-quality softcover or the "Collector's Edition", even plusher and thicker than the previous hardcover.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] Each is usually about 80 pages and has more "relevant" features and shorter articles than in the early years, but the scope and direction and purpose had not changed.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] On May 17, 2007, the magazine, published on a bimonthly basis, announced that it had stopped publication, at least temporarily, with the April/May 2007 issue." On October 27, 2007, Edwin S.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] Grosvenor, purchased the magazine from Forbes for $500,000 in cash and $10 million in subscription liabilities.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] Grosvenor, who serves as president and editor-in-chief, is the former editor of the fine arts magazine, *Portfolio*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] Grosvenor was also the editor of the literary magazine, *Current Books*, and magazines for Marriott and Hyatt Hotels.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] He was also the CEO of KnowledgeMax, Inc., an online bookseller.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] After suspending print publication in 2013, the magazine relaunched digitally in 2017 with a new website and subscriber management system.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] For a magazine that has lasted seven decades, its way of covering history has changed much over the years.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] Each issue is still an eclectic collection of articles on the people, places, and events from the entire history of the United States.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] Today, there is mention of television shows and Web sites, and a greater diversity of articles such as Harvard professor Henry Louis Gates' 2012 article, "Growing Up Colored," about life as a young boy in segregated West Virginia.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] Recent content has included a special 70th Anniversary issue on "What Makes America Great" (Winter 2020) and an issue on the history of gun control with essays by historian Joseph J.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] Ellis, law professor Adam Winkler, and gun rights advocate Robert A.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] Some historians have criticized the magazine for what they say is a lack of seriousness.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] During the early 1960s, *American Heritage* sponsored a series of popular military board games produced by the Milton Bradley Company.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] Beginning in 1973, and presumably as part of the then-current national lead-up to the Bicentennial, *American Heritage* teamed up with producer David L.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] Wolper for a series of four hour-long television specials (broadcast every few months between late 1973 and early 1975) based on events and people in American history, in documentary-like filmed dramatizations with actors taking the roles of historic figures, and key events re-enacted.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] The specials, sponsored by Texaco, were narrated by actor Cliff Robertson and broadcast on ABC.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] In 1976, the American Heritage Publishing Company founded and sponsored an award called the Samuel Eliot Morison Award, named for the historian Samuel Eliot Morison.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] It had the goal of annually honoring an American author whose work shows "that good history is literature as well as high scholarship." The first award was presented on September 28, 1977, by Henry A.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/american-heritage-magazine] Kissinger at the Pierpont Morgan Library, valued at $5,000.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anisfield-wolf-award] The **Anisfield-Wolf Book Award** is an American literary award dedicated to honoring written works that make important contributions to the understanding of racism and the appreciation of the rich diversity of human culture.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anisfield-wolf-award] Established in 1935 by Cleveland poet and philanthropist Edith Anisfield Wolf and originally administered by the *Saturday Review*, the awards have been administered by the Cleveland Foundation since 1963.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anisfield-wolf-award] The foundation confers awards in several categories, such as fiction, poetry, nonfiction, memoir/autobiography, and lifetime achievement, each September in a ceremony free and open to the public and attended by the honorees.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anisfield-wolf-award] Winners previously include Zora Neale Hurston (1943), Langston Hughes (1954), Martin Luther King Jr.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anisfield-wolf-award] When Montagu retired in 1996, Gates assumed the chair position.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anisfield-wolf-award] In 1996, evolutionary biologist Stephen Jay Gould, writer Joyce Carol Oates, and historian Simon Schama (all of whom retired before the 2024 awards) joined.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anisfield-wolf-award] After Gould died in 2002, psychologist Steven Pinker replaced him on the jury.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anisfield-wolf-award] At the 2024 awards, Pinker and Dove retired.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anisfield-wolf-award] The current jury is Natasha Trethewey (jury chair), Peter Ho Davies, Tiya Miles, Charles King, Deesha Philyaw, and Luis Alberto Urrea.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] In the late 1970s, she became the creative director of NASA's Voyager Interstellar Message Project, which produced the golden discs affixed to both the *Voyager 1* and *Voyager 2* spacecraft.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] She also published a novel, *A Famous Broken Heart*, in 1977, and later co-wrote several best selling non-fiction books with Sagan.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] Ann Druyan was born in Queens, New York, the daughter of Pearl A.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] (née Goldsmith) and Harry Druyan, who co-owned a knitwear firm.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] Druyan's early interest in math and science was, in her word, "derailed" when a junior high-school teacher ridiculed a question she asked about the universality of π.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] "I raised my hand and said, 'You mean this applies to every circle in the universe?', and the teacher told me not to ask stupid questions.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] And there I was having this religious experience, and she made me feel like such a fool.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] In the late 1970s, Druyan became the creative director of NASA's Voyager Interstellar Message Project.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] As creative director, Druyan worked with a team to design a complex message, including music and images, for possible alien civilizations.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] These golden phonograph records affixed to the *Voyager 1* and *Voyager 2* spacecraft are now beyond the outermost planets of the Solar System, and *Voyager 1* has entered interstellar space.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] Both records have a projected shelf life of one billion years.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] Druyan's role on the project was discussed on the July 8, 2018, 60 Minutes segment "The Little Spacecraft That Could".
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] In the segment, Druyan explained her insistence that Chuck Berry's "Johnny B.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] Goode" be included on the Golden Record, saying: "...*Johnny B.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] Goode*, rock and roll, was the music of motion, of moving, getting to someplace you've never been before, and the odds are against you, but you want to go.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] That was Voyager." The segment also discussed Sagan's suggestion, in 1990, that *Voyager 1* turn its cameras back towards Earth to take a series of photographs showing the planets of the Solar System.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] The shots, showing Earth from a distance of 3.7 billion miles as a small point of bluish light, became the basis for Sagan's famous "Pale Blue Dot" passage, first published in *Pale Blue Dot: A Vision of the Human Future in Space* (1994).
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] During that time, Druyan also co-wrote (with Carl Sagan and Steven Soter) the 1980 PBS documentary series *Cosmos*, hosted by Carl Sagan.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] The thirteen-part series covered a wide range of scientific subjects, including the origin of life and a perspective of humans place in the universe.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] It was highly acclaimed, and became the most widely watched series in the history of American public television at that time.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] The series won two Emmys and a Peabody Award, and has since been broadcast in more than 60 countries and seen by over 500 million people.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] A book was also published to accompany the series.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] As of 2009, it is still the most widely watched PBS series in the world.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] Several revised versions of the series were later broadcast; one version, telecast after Sagan's death, opens with Druyan paying tribute to her late husband and the impact of *Cosmos* over the years.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] Druyan wrote and produced the 1987 PBS *NOVA* episode "Confessions of a Weaponeer" on the life of President Eisenhower's Science Advisor George Kistiakowsky.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] In 2000, Druyan, together with Steve Soter, co-wrote *Passport to the Universe*, the inaugural planetarium show for the Rose Center for Earth and Space at the American Natural History Museum's Hayden Planetarium.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] The attraction is narrated by Tom Hanks.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] Druyan and Soter also co-wrote *The Search for Life: Are We Alone*, narrated by Harrison Ford, which also debuted at the Hayden's Rose Center.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] In 2000, Druyan co-founded Cosmos Studios, Inc, with Joseph Firmage.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] As CEO of Cosmos Studios, Druyan produces science-based entertainment for all media.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] In addition to *Cosmos: A SpaceTime Odyssey*, Cosmos Studios has produced *Cosmic Africa*, *Lost Dinosaurs of Egypt*, and the Emmy-nominated documentary *Cosmic Journey: The Voyager Interstellar Mission and Message*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] In 2009, she distributed a series of podcasts called *At Home in the Cosmos with Annie Druyan*, in which she described her works, the life of her husband, Carl Sagan, and their marriage.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] Druyan is credited, with Carl Sagan, as the co-creator and co-producer of the 1997 feature film *Contact*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] In 2011, it was announced that Druyan would executive produce, co-write, and be one of the episodic directors for a sequel to *Cosmos: A Personal Voyage*, to be called *Cosmos: A Spacetime Odyssey*, which began airing in March 2014.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] Episodes premiered on Fox and also aired on National Geographic Channel on the following night.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] At the time of its release, Fox gave the series the largest global rollout of a television series ever, debuting it in 180 countries.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] The premiere episode was shown across nine of Fox's cable properties in addition to the broadcast network in a "roadblock" style premiere.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] The series went on to become the most-watched series ever for National Geographic Channel International, with at least some part of the 13-episode series watched by 135 million people, including 45 million in the U.S.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] In March 2020, a third season of *Cosmos*, named *Cosmos: Possible Worlds*, for which Druyan was executive producer, writer, and director, premiered on National Geographic.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] Druyan also said: "I very much have season four in mind, and I know what it's going to be.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] Druyan's first novel, *A Famous Broken Heart*, was published in 1977.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] Druyan co-wrote six *New York Times* bestsellers with Carl Sagan, including: *Comet*, *Shadows of Forgotten Ancestors*, and *The Demon-Haunted World*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] She is co-author, along with Carl Sagan, F.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] Drake, Timothy Ferris, Jon Lomberg and Linda Salzman Sagan, of *Murmurs Of Earth: The Voyager Interstellar Record*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] She also wrote the updated introduction to Sagan's book *The Cosmic Connection* and the epilogue of *Billions and Billions*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] She wrote the introduction to, and edited *The Varieties of Scientific Experience*, published from Sagan's 1985 Gifford lectures.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] In February 2020, Druyan published *Cosmos: Possible Worlds*, a companion volume to the television series of the same name, which premiered in March 2020.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] Druyan is a fellow of the Committee for the Scientific Investigation of Claims of the Paranormal (CSICOP).
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] Druyan served as program director of the first solar-sail deep-space mission, Cosmos 1, launched on a Russian ICBM in 2005.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] Druyan is involved in multiple Breakthrough Initiatives.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] With Frank Drake, Druyan is the co-chair of Breakthrough Message and also a member of Breakthrough Starshot.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] She is a member of the advisory board of The Carl Sagan Institute.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] Druyan has for many years been a vocal advocate for nuclear disarmament.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] She was arrested three times at the Mercury, Nevada nuclear test site during Mikhail Gorbachev's unilateral moratorium on underground nuclear testing, with which President Ronald Reagan did not cooperate.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] This included an arrest in June 1986, when she crossed a white painted line indicating the test site's boundary.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] Sagan, who attended the same protest with Druyan, was not arrested.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] In the early 1990s, Druyan worked with Sagan and then-Senator Al Gore Jr. and a host of religious and scientific leaders to bring the scientific and religious worlds together in a unified effort to preserve the environment, resulting in the *Declaration of the 'Mission to Washington'*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] She was a founding director of the Children's Health Fund until the spring of 2004, a project that provides mobile pediatric care to homeless and disadvantaged children in more than half a dozen cities.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] She is currently a member of their advisory board.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] She has been on the board of directors of the National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws (NORML) for over 10 years and was its president from 2006 to 2010.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] An asteroid discovered in 1988 was named in Druyan's honor by its discoverer Eleanor F.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] In a 2020 interview with *Skeptical Inquirer*, Druyan discussed 4970 Druyan and the asteroid named after her late husband, saying that 4970 Druyan is in a "wedding ring orbit" around the Sun with 2709 Sagan.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] In November 2006, Druyan was a speaker at "Beyond Belief: Science, Religion, Reason and Survival".
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] In January 2007, she was a juror at the 2007 Sundance Film Festival, responsible for selecting the winner of the Alfred P.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] Sloan Prize for films about science and technology.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] In November 2007, Druyan was awarded the title of "Humanist Laureate" by the International Academy of Humanism.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] In October 2019, the Center for Inquiry West opened the Carl Sagan–Ann Druyan Theater in Los Angeles.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] In an interview with Joel Achenbach of *The Washington Post*, Druyan said that her early interest in science stemmed from a fascination with Karl Marx.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] Achenbach commented that "She had, at the time, rather vaporous standards of evidence", a reference to her belief in the ancient astronauts of Erich von Däniken and the theories of Immanuel Velikovsky pertaining to the solar system.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] The asteroid 4970 Druyan, which is in a companion orbit with asteroid 2709 Sagan named after Druyan's late husband, is named after Druyan.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] In 2015, it was announced that Warner Brothers was in development on a drama about Sagan and Druyan's relationship, to be produced by producer Lynda Obst and Druyan.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] In 2020, Sagan and Druyan's daughter Sasha Sagan released a book *For Small Creatures Such As We: Rituals for Finding Meaning in our Unlikely World*, which discusses life with her parents and her father's death when she was fourteen years old.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/ann-druyan] Druyan also gave Sasha a recurring role in *Cosmos: Possible Worlds*, where she played her own grandmother, including in the episode *Man of a Trillion Worlds*, which featured the life of Carl Sagan.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain graduated from the Culinary Institute of America in 1978.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He worked in many professional kitchens, including several years as an executive chef at Brasserie Les Halles in Manhattan.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In the late 1990s, *The New Yorker* published an essay by Bourdain, kickstarting Bourdain's career and legitimizing the point-blank tone that became his trademark.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] The success was followed a year later by the *New York Times* best-selling book *Kitchen Confidential: Adventures in the Culinary Underbelly* (2000).
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain's first food and world-travel television show, *A Cook's Tour*, ran for 35 episodes on the Food Network in 2002 and 2003.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In 2005, he began hosting the Travel Channel's culinary and cultural adventure programs *Anthony Bourdain: No Reservations* (2005–2012) and *The Layover* (2011–2013).
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In 2013, he began a three-season run as a judge on *The Taste* and consequently switched his travelogue programming to CNN to host *Anthony Bourdain: Parts Unknown*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain also wrote fiction and historical nonfiction.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] On June 8, 2018, Bourdain died while on location in France, filming for *Parts Unknown*, of suicide by hanging.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Anthony Michael Bourdain was born in Manhattan on June 25, 1956.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] His father, Pierre, was a classical music recording industry executive.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] His mother, Gladys (née Sacksman), was a *New York Times* editor.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Anthony's younger brother, Christopher, was born a few years after him.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Anthony grew up living with both of his parents and described his childhood in one of his books: "I did not want for love or attention.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] God was never mentioned so I was annoyed by neither church nor any notion of sin or damnation." His father was Catholic of French descent and his mother was Jewish.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain stated that, although he was considered Jewish by halacha's definition, "I've never been in a synagogue.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] But that doesn't make me any less Jewish, I don't think." His family was not religious.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] At the time of Bourdain's birth, Pierre was a salesman at a New York City camera store as well as a floor manager at a record store.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He later became an executive for Columbia Records, and Gladys was a staff editor at *The New York Times*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain's paternal grandparents were French (his great-grandfather Aurélien Bourdain was born in Brazil to French parents) and his paternal grandfather Pierre Michel Bourdain emigrated from Arcachon to New York following World War I.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain's father spent summers in France as a boy and grew up speaking French.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain spent most of his childhood in Leonia, New Jersey.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He felt jealous of the lack of parental supervision of his classmates and the freedom they had in their homes.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In his youth, Bourdain was a member of the Boy Scouts of America.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain's love of food was kindled in his youth while on a family vacation in France.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He first experienced two "pre-epiphanies" with the first being the vichyssoise served cold on the voyage to France on the Queen Mary, and the second was the realization that French children were allowed to have a cigarette on Sunday and allowed to drink vin ordinaire at dinner.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] The vichyssoise was an eye-opener to him because he had previously only experienced hot soup made from condensed canned soups.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He described it in *Kitchen Confidential* as the "first food I really noticed.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] It was the first food I enjoyed and, more important, remembered enjoying." Later in the trip, while staying with his aunt in La Teste de Buch, his family went out on an oyster fisherman's boat.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain had never eaten a raw oyster before, but the fisherman offered him one which he had just harvested.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain described the experience as "Everything was different now.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] This, I knew was the magic I had until now been only dimly and spitefully aware of.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He graduated from the Dwight-Englewood School, an independent coeducational college-preparatory day school in Englewood, New Jersey, in 1973, then enrolled at Vassar College but dropped out after two years.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He worked at seafood restaurants in Provincetown, Massachusetts, including the Lobster Pot, while attending Vassar, which inspired his decision to pursue cooking as a career.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain attended the Culinary Institute of America, graduating in 1978.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] From there he went on to run various restaurant kitchens in New York City, including the Supper Club, One Fifth Avenue and Sullivan's.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In 1998, Bourdain became an executive chef at Brasserie Les Halles.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Based in Manhattan, at the time the brand had additional restaurants in Miami; Washington, D.C.; and Tokyo.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain remained an executive chef there for many years and even when no longer formally employed at Les Halles, he maintained a relationship with the restaurant, which described him in January 2014 as their "chef at large".
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Les Halles closed in 2017 after filing for bankruptcy.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In the mid-1980s, Bourdain began submitting unsolicited work for publication to *Between C & D*, a literary magazine of the Lower East Side.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] The magazine eventually published a piece that Bourdain had written about a chef who was trying to purchase heroin on the Lower East Side.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In 1985, Bourdain signed up for a writing workshop with Gordon Lish.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In 1990, Bourdain received a small book advance from Random House, after meeting a Random House editor.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] His first book, a culinary mystery called *Bone in the Throat*, was published in 1995.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He paid for his own book tour, but he did not find success.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] His second mystery book, *Gone Bamboo,* also performed poorly in sales.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] *Kitchen Confidential: Adventures in the Culinary Underbelly*, a 2000 *New York Times* bestseller, was an expansion of his 1999 *New Yorker* article "Don't Eat Before Reading This".
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In 2010, he published *Medium Raw: A Bloody Valentine to the World of Food and the People Who Cook*, a memoir and follow-up to the book *Kitchen Confidential*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain later published a hypothetical historical investigation, *Typhoid Mary: An Urban Historical*, about Mary Mallon, an Irish-born cook believed to have infected 53 people with typhoid fever between 1907 and 1938.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In 2007, Bourdain published *No Reservations: Around the World on an Empty Stomach*, covering the experiences of filming and photographs of the first three seasons of the show and his crew at work while filming the series.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] His blog for the third season of *Top Chef* was nominated for a Webby Award for Best Blog (in the Cultural/Personal category) in 2008.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In 2012, Bourdain co-wrote the graphic novel *Get Jiro!* with Joel Rose, with art by Langdon Foss.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] It will receive an adult animated series adaptation produced by Warner Bros.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In 2015, Bourdain joined the travel, food, and politics publication Roads & Kingdoms, as the site's sole investor and editor-at-large.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Over the next few years, Bourdain contributed to the site and edited the Dispatched By Bourdain series.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain and Roads & Kingdoms also partnered on the digital series *Explore Parts Unknown*, which launched in 2017 and won a Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Short Form Nonfiction or Reality Series in 2018.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain hosted many food and travel series, including his first show, *A Cook's Tour* (2002 to 2003).
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He worked for The Travel Channel from 2005 to 2013.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He also worked for CNN from 2013 to 2018.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain described the concept as, "I travel around the world, eat a lot of shit, and basically do whatever the fuck I want." His programs focused on the exploration of international culture, cuisine, and the human condition.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Nigella Lawson noted that Bourdain had an "incredibly beautiful style when he talks that ranges from erudite to brilliantly slangy".
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] The acclaim surrounding Bourdain's memoir *Kitchen Confidential* led to an offer by the Food Network for him to host his own food and world-travel show, *A Cook's Tour*, which premiered in January 2002.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In July 2005, he premiered a new, somewhat similar television series, *Anthony Bourdain: No Reservations*, on the Travel Channel.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] As a further result of the immense popularity of *Kitchen Confidential*, the Fox sitcom *Kitchen Confidential* aired in 2005, in which the character Jack Bourdain is based loosely on Anthony Bourdain's biography and persona.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In July 2006, he and his crew were in Beirut filming an episode of *No Reservations* when the Israel–Lebanon conflict broke out unexpectedly after the crew had filmed only a few hours of footage.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Wolf* after Harvey Keitel's character in *Pulp Fiction*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain and his crew were finally evacuated with other American citizens, on the morning of July 20, by the United States Marine Corps.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] The Beirut *No Reservations* episode, which aired on August 21, 2006, was nominated for an Emmy Award in 2007.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In July 2011, the Travel Channel announced adding a second one-hour, 10-episode Bourdain show to be titled *The Layover*, which premiered November 21, 2011.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Each episode featured an exploration of a city that can be undertaken within an air travel layover of 24 to 48 hours.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] The series ran for 20 episodes, through February 2013.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain executive produced a similar show hosted by celebrities called *The Getaway*, which lasted two seasons on Esquire Network.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In May 2012, Bourdain announced that he was leaving the Travel Channel.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He went on to host *Anthony Bourdain: Parts Unknown* for CNN.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] The program focused on other cuisines, cultures and politics and premiered on April 14, 2013.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] President Barack Obama was featured on the program in an episode filmed in Vietnam that aired in September 2016; the two talked over a beer and bun cha at a small restaurant in Hanoi.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] The show was filmed and is set in places as diverse as Libya, Tokyo, the Punjab region, Jamaica, Turkey, Ethiopia, Nigeria, Far West Texas and Armenia.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Between 2012 and 2017, he served as narrator and executive producer for several episodes of the award-winning PBS series *The Mind of a Chef*; it aired on the last months of each year.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] The series moved from PBS to Facebook Watch in 2017.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] From 2013 to 2015, Bourdain was an executive producer and appeared as a judge and mentor in ABC's cooking-competition show *The Taste*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He earned an Emmy nomination for each season.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain appeared five times as guest judge on Bravo's *Top Chef* reality cooking competition program.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He was also one of the main judges on *Top Chef All-Stars* (*Top Chef*, Season 8).
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He made a guest appearance on the August 6, 2007, New York City episode of *Bizarre Foods with Andrew Zimmern*, and Zimmern himself appeared as a guest on the New York City episode of Bourdain's *No Reservations* airing the same day.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] On October 20, 2008, Bourdain hosted a special, *At the Table with Anthony Bourdain*, on the Travel Channel.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain was a consultant and writer for the television series *Treme*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In 2011, he voiced himself in a cameo on an episode of *The Simpsons* titled "The Food Wife", in which Marge, Lisa, and Bart start a food blog called *The Three Mouthkateers*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He appeared in a 2013 episode of the animated series *Archer* (S04E07), voicing chef Lance Casteau, a parody of himself.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In 2015, he voiced a fictionalized version of himself on an episode of *Sanjay and Craig* titled "Snake Parts Unknown".
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] From 2015 to 2017, Bourdain hosted *Raw Craft*, a series of short videos released on YouTube.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] The series followed Bourdain as he visited various artisans who produce various craft items by hand, including iron skillets, suits, saxophones, and kitchen knives.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] The series was produced by William Grant & Sons to promote their Balvenie distillery's products.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In September 2011, Ecco Press announced that Bourdain would have his own publishing line, Anthony Bourdain Books, which included acquiring between three and five titles per year that "reflect his remarkably eclectic tastes".
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] The first books that the imprint published, released in 2013, include *L.A.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Son: My Life, My City, My Food* by Roy Choi, Tien Nguyen, and Natasha Phan, *Prophets of Smoked Meat* by Daniel Vaughn, *Pain Don't Hurt* by Mark Miller, and *Grand Forks: A History of American Dining in 128 Reviews* by Marilyn Hagerty.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In describing the line, he said, "This will be a line of books for people with strong voices who are *good* at something—who speak with authority.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Discern nothing from this initial list—other than a general affection for people who cook food and like food.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] The ability to kick people in the head is just as compelling to us—as long as that's coupled with an ability to vividly describe the experience.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] We are just as intent on crossing genres as we are enthusiastic about our first three authors.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] It only gets weirder from here." Shortly after Bourdain's death, HarperCollins announced that the publishing line would be shut down after the remaining works under contract were published.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain appeared as himself in the 2015 film *The Big Short*, in which he used seafood stew as an analogy for a collateralized debt obligation.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He also produced and starred in *Wasted!
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Drew Magary, in a column for *GQ* published on the day of Bourdain's death, opined that Bourdain was the spiritual successor to Hunter S.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Tributes declared Bourdain "the original rock star" of the culinary world, and his public persona that of a "culinary bad boy".
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Due to his liberal use of profanity and sexual references in his television show *No Reservations*, the network added viewer-discretion advisories to each episode.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain was known for consuming local specialty dishes his audiences found exotic, including black-colored blood sausages called *mustamakkara* (lit.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] 'black sausage') in Finland, "sheep testicles in Morocco, ant eggs in Puebla, Mexico, a raw seal eyeball as part of a traditional Inuit seal hunt, and an entire cobra—beating heart, blood, bile, and meat—in Vietnam".
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain was quoted as saying that a Chicken McNugget was the most disgusting thing he ever ate, but he was fond of Popeyes and Jolibee chicken.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He also declared that the unwashed warthog rectum he ate in Namibia was "the worst meal of [his] life", along with the fermented shark he ate in Iceland.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain was noted for his put-downs of celebrity chefs such as Paula Deen, Bobby Flay, Guy Fieri, Sandra Lee, and Rachael Ray, and appeared irritated by both the overt commercialism of the celebrity cooking industry and its lack of culinary authenticity.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He voiced a "serious disdain for food demigods like Alan Richman, Alice Waters, and Alain Ducasse".
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain recognized the irony of his transformation into a celebrity chef and began to qualify his insults; in the 2007 New Orleans episode of *No Reservations*, he reconciled with Emeril Lagasse, whom he had previously disparaged in *Kitchen Confidential*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He later wrote more favorably of Lagasse in the preface of the 2013 edition.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He was outspoken in his praise for chefs he admired, particularly Ferran Adrià, Juan Mari Arzak, Fergus Henderson, José Andrés, Thomas Keller, Martin Picard, Éric Ripert, and Marco Pierre White, as well as his former protégé and colleagues at Brasserie Les Halles.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He spoke very highly of Julia Child, citing her as an influence.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain was known for his sarcastic comments about vegan and vegetarian activists, considering their lifestyle "rude" to the inhabitants of many countries he visited.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He considered vegetarianism, except in the case of religious exemptions, a "First World luxury".
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] However, he also believed that Americans eat too much meat, and admired vegetarians and vegans who put aside their beliefs when visiting different cultures as a sign of respect to their hosts.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain's book *The Nasty Bits* is dedicated to "Joey, Johnny, and Dee Dee" of the Ramones.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He declared appreciation for their music, as well as that of other early punk bands such as Dead Boys and The Voidoids.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He said that the playing of music by Billy Joel, Elton John, or Grateful Dead in his kitchen was grounds for firing.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Joel was a fan of Bourdain's, and visited the restaurant.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] On *No Reservations* and *Parts Unknown*, he dined with and interviewed many musicians, both in the U.S. and elsewhere, with a special focus on glam and various rockers such as Alice Cooper, David Johansen, Marky Ramone, and Iggy Pop.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He featured contemporary band Queens of the Stone Age on *No Reservations* several times, and they composed and performed the theme song for *Parts Unknown*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In the 1970s, while attending high school at Dwight-Englewood School, Bourdain dated Nancy Putkoski.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He described her as "a bad girl", older than he was and "part of a druggy crowd".
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] She was a year ahead of him and Bourdain graduated one year early in order to follow Putkoski to Vassar College since they had just started admitting men.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He studied there between the ages of 17 and 19.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He then attended The Culinary Institute of America, a 15-minute drive from Vassar.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] The couple married in 1985 and remained together for two decades, divorcing in 2005.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] On April 20, 2007, he married Ottavia Busia.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain said having to be away from his family for 250 days a year working on his television shows put a strain on the relationship.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Busia appeared in several episodes of *No Reservations*, notably the ones in Tuscany, Rome, Rio de Janeiro, Naples, and her birthplace of Sardinia.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain met Italian actress Asia Argento in 2016 while filming the Rome episode of *Parts Unknown*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In October 2017, Argento said in an article in *The New Yorker* that she had been sexually assaulted by Harvey Weinstein in the 1990s.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] After being criticized for her account in Italian media and politics, Argento moved to Germany to escape what she described as a culture of "victim blaming" in Italy.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Argento delivered a speech on May 20, 2018, following the 2018 Cannes Film Festival, calling the festival Weinstein's "hunting ground" and alleging that she was raped by Weinstein in Cannes when she was 21.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] She added, "And even tonight, sitting among you, there are those who still have to be held accountable for their conduct against women." Bourdain supported her during that period.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] On June 3, 2018, Bourdain tweeted a video where the team was celebrating during the production of the show with Argento as director, him and Christopher Doyle.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In August 2018, Argento said that Bourdain handled the payment of $380,000 to Jimmy Bennett, who had accused Argento of sexually assaulting him.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain practiced the martial art Brazilian jiu-jitsu, earning a blue belt in August 2015.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He won gold at the IBJJF New York Spring International Open Championship in 2016, in the Middleweight Master 5 (age 51 and older) division.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain was known to be a heavy smoker.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In a nod to Bourdain's two-pack-a-day cigarette habit, Thomas Keller once served him a 20-course tasting menu which included a mid-meal "coffee and cigarette", a coffee custard infused with tobacco with a foie gras mousse.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain stopped smoking in 2007 for his daughter, but relapsed towards the end of his life.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain wrote in *Kitchen Confidential* of his experience in a SoHo restaurant in 1981, where he and his friends were often high.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain said drugs influenced his decisions and that he would send a busboy to Alphabet City to obtain cannabis, methaqualone, cocaine, LSD, psilocybin mushrooms, secobarbital, tuinal, amphetamine, codeine and heroin.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In early June 2018, Bourdain was working on an episode of *Parts Unknown* in Strasbourg with his frequent collaborator and friend Éric Ripert.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] On June 8, 2018, Ripert became worried when Bourdain had missed dinner and breakfast.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He subsequently found Bourdain dead of suicide by hanging in his room at Le Chambard hotel in Kaysersberg near Colmar.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Texting records show that Bourdain had argued with Asia Argento in the days leading to his death, with Argento ending their relationship shortly before his suicide.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain's body bore no signs of violence, and his suicide appeared to be an impulsive act.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Rocquigny du Fayel disclosed that Bourdain's toxicology results were negative for narcotics, showing only a trace of a therapeutic non-narcotic medication.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain's body was cremated in France on June 13, 2018, and his ashes were returned to the United States two days later, before being given to his brother Christopher.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain's mother, Gladys Bourdain, told *The New York Times*, "He is absolutely the last person in the world I would have ever dreamed would do something like this. [...] He had everything.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Following the news of Bourdain's death, various public figures expressed condolences.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Among them were fellow chefs Andrew Zimmern and Gordon Ramsay, former astronaut Scott Kelly, and then-U.S. president Donald Trump.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] To make us a little less afraid of the unknown." On the day of Bourdain's death, CNN aired *Remembering Anthony Bourdain*, a tribute program.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In the days following Bourdain's death, fans gathered to pay tribute to him outside his former place of employment, Brasserie Les Halles (which had closed down the previous year).
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Cooks and restaurant owners held gatherings, tribute dinners, and memorials, and donated the net revenue from these events to the National Suicide Prevention Lifeline.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In August 2018, CNN announced a final, posthumous season of *Parts Unknown*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Its remaining episodes were completed using narration and additional interviews from featured guests with the season including two retrospective episodes paying tribute to the series and to Bourdain's legacy.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In June 2019, Éric Ripert and José Andrés proclaimed the first annual Bourdain Day as a tribute to Bourdain.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] That month, the Culinary Institute of America (CIA) established a scholarship in Bourdain's honor.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] A collection of Bourdain's personal items were sold at auction in October 2019, raising $1.8 million, part of which went to support the Anthony Bourdain Legacy Scholarship at his alma mater, the Culinary Institute of America.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] His custom-made Bob Kramer Steel and Meteorite Chef's Knife sold for the highest price, a record $231,250.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In June 2021, a documentary film directed by Morgan Neville and produced by CNN Films and HBO Max titled *Roadrunner: A Film About Anthony Bourdain*, had its world premiere at the Tribeca Film Festival.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] It was released by Focus Features on July 16, 2021.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In October 2022, *Down and Out in Paradise: The Life of Anthony Bourdain*, an unauthorized biography of Bourdain, was published.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In August 2024, a biopic of Bourdain titled *Tony* was announced to be in the works with A24 in negotiations to acquire the film, with Matt Johnson attached to direct and Dominic Sessa attached to star as Bourdain.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In an assessment of Bourdain's life for *The Nation*, David Klion wrote that, "Bourdain understood that the point of journalism is to tell the truth, to challenge the powerful, to expose wrongdoing.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] But his unique gift was to make doing all that look fun rather than grim or tedious." According to Klion, Bourdain's shows "made it possible to believe that social justice and earthly delights weren't mutually exclusive, and he pursued both with the same earnest reverence".
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain advocated for communicating the value of traditional or peasant foods, including all of the varietal bits and unused animal parts not usually eaten by affluent 21st-century Americans.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He also praised the quality of freshly prepared street food in other countries—especially developing countries—compared to fast-food chains in the U.S.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Regarding Western moral criticism of cuisine in developing countries, Bourdain stated: "Let's call this criticism what it is: *racism*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] There are a lot of practices from the developing world that I find personally repellent, from my privileged Western point of view.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] With regard to criticism of the Chinese, Bourdain stated: "The way in which people dismiss whole centuries-old cultures—often older than their own and usually non-white—with just utter contempt aggravates me.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] People who suggest I shouldn't go to a country like China, look at or film it, because some people eat dog there, I find that racist, frankly.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Understand people first: their economic, living situation." Regarding the myth that monosodium glutamate in Chinese food is unhealthy, Bourdain said: "It's a lie.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] You know what causes Chinese restaurant syndrome?
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He championed industrious Spanish-speaking immigrants—from Mexico, Ecuador, and other Central and South American countries—who are cooks and chefs in many United States restaurants, including upscale establishments, regardless of cuisine.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] He considered them talented chefs and invaluable cooks, underpaid and unrecognized even though they have become the backbone of the U.S. restaurant industry.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] In 2017, Bourdain became a vocal advocate against sexual harassment in the restaurant industry, speaking out about celebrity chefs Mario Batali and John Besh, and in Hollywood, particularly following his then-girlfriend Asia Argento's sexual abuse allegations against Harvey Weinstein.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/anthony-bourdain] Bourdain accused Hollywood director Quentin Tarantino of "complicity" in the Weinstein sex scandal.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] Ward was born in Newark, Ohio, and is a graduate of Oberlin College (1962), where he majored in art.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] Champion Ward, educator and a vice-president of the Ford Foundation.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] Ward's great-grandfather was Ferdinand Ward, a 19th-century swindler whose ponzi scheme led to a financial crash which bankrupted many investors, including Ulysses S.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] Ward wrote a book about the story of his great-grandfather, *A Disposition to be Rich,* in 2012.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] Ward was the founding editor of *Audience Magazine* (1970–1973) and the editor of *American Heritage Magazine* (1977–1982).
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] Roosevelt, *A First-class Temperament: the Emergence of Franklin Roosevelt*, won the National Book Critics Circle Award and the Francis Parkman Prize of the Society of American Historians and was a finalist for the Pulitzer Prize.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] Ward has been a long-time collaborator of American documentary filmmaker Ken Burns.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] Ward wrote the script for the Ken Burns series, *The American Revolution* to be shown on PBS for six consecutive days at 8:00 PM, November 16-21, 2025.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] PBS has an "inside look" at the TV series online.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] The principal writer of the television mini-series *The Civil War* (1990), Ward has collaborated with its co-producer Ken Burns on most of the documentaries he has made since, including *Jazz*, *Baseball*, *The War*, and *The Vietnam War*.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] The films with Burns have garnered him five Emmy Awards.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] He has won an additional two Emmys for *The Kennedys* (1992), and *TR, The Story of Theodore Roosevelt* (1996).
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] His script for the documentary *Unforgivable Blackness: The Rise and Fall of Jack Johnson*, won the Writers Guild of America Award in 2005, and the accompanying book won the 2006 William Hill Sports Book of the Year and the Anisfield-Wolf Award for best biography.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] The 2011 Burns/Ward collaboration, *Prohibition*, brought Ward his seventh Emmy for Outstanding Writing for Nonfiction Programming.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] Since that project, he worked with Ken Burns on *The Roosevelts: An Intimate History*, a seven-part documentary miniseries depicting the lives of Theodore Roosevelt, Franklin D.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] Roosevelt, and Eleanor Roosevelt, (broadcast on PBS in September 2014), and a multi-part TV series "The Vietnam War", with Lynn Novick and Ken Burns (broadcast on PBS in September 2017).
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] In 2012, Ward published a biography of his great-grandfather Ferdinand Ward (1851–1925), known as the greatest swindler of the Gilded Age.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] *A Disposition to be Rich* was written with the assistance of private family materials.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] Ward spent some of his boyhood years in India and has remained involved with India and in Indian issues.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] Working and writing about the ongoing struggle to save the Bengal tiger in the wild has meant friendships with great tiger men like Fateh Singh Rathore and Billy Arjan Singh.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] His essays and pieces on India have appeared in a wide array of publications, including *Geo*, *Audubon*, *National Geographic*, *Smithsonian*, *Aperture* and others.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] In 2011, he wrote an introduction for the book *Varanasi: Portrait of a Civilization,* (Collins, India,) by the photographer *Raghu Rai,* with whom he has collaborated on magazine pieces.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] He is currently at work on a book about the partition of the Indian subcontinent.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] "I think jazz music is so important to this country....
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] Ward is married to the writer and social/environmental activist Diane Raines Ward.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] When he was nine years old, Ward contracted poliomyelitis, and wears leg braces.
[src:geoffrey-c-ward/geoffrey-c-ward] He later cited Franklin Roosevelt as a source of inspiration on how to overcome his handicap.
